Scotland’s independent schools have broken records for academic achievement by staying the same way in 2018 and have once again demonstrated exceptional exam results, reinforced by individual and collective achievements in sports, the arts, music and other community endeavors.
With a total of more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the highest possible level of service to their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, for their chosen careers, and to be global citizens.
As we work in the education sector, which can design and implement the intended school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and are eagerly sought after in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you can talk to someone in a language they understand, they’ll understand you with their mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will speak to his heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely on English alone if we want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
Based on the results of recent exams this year, we can say that languages are at the peak of popularity and have the best retention ratings in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of foreign language learners received the highest A score.
The data collected from 74 schools that are members of SCIS showed that 72 percent of students received the highest A rating during the Mandarin exam, the highest A rating was received by 72 percent of German learners, and the highest A rating was received by 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland regard foreign language proficiency as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as an elective are now considered as important as basic subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills found that of all the reasons employers struggled to fill jobs, 17% had insufficient language skills.
As a result, language skills are increasingly becoming a must for young people to be prepared for their future careers.
As languages will play a key role in future employability, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career a person chooses to have a second language, he or she will be much better off in the future if he or she has these lifelong skills.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will make a person who speaks several languages much more competitive.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 per cent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to be interviewed, while French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of people, i.e. 15 per cent.
That is why investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
By learning several languages, especially in developing countries, children will have a better chance of meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school differs according to the language it teaches.
While a number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, others focus on languages that are considered the most important in the UK, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interests are, there will always be plenty of languages to choose from at an independent school with teaching staff and experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a teaching environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to live in the future.
It is undeniable that in today’s global business environment, languages remain vital for the country’s future, so this must be reflected in the education system as well.
In fact, modern languages should certainly be regarded as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and performance to Scottish young people.
This must be done.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Board of Independent Schools
