North Korea Says It Will Not Disarm Unilaterally Without Confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were deepening their mistrust of the United States and that under such circumstances the country would certainly not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri told the General Assembly that North Korea has taken "significant measures of good will" over the past year, including halting nuclear missile tests, dismantling its nuclear test base and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We have not received a similar response from the US side," he said.
“Without any confidence in the U.S., we will not be able to rely on our national security, and under no circumstances will we unilaterally disarm the former.”
While Ri repeated past complaints about Washington’s opposition to a phased approach to nuclear disarmament that would reward North Korea in phases, his statement stood out because he did not entirely rule out the idea of bilateral disarmament, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri alluded to a joint statement made by Kim and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on "disarmament of the Korean peninsula" and Trump pledged to ensure North Korea's security.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also refused to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. is demanding nuclear disarmament first and is increasing pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal through coercive methods, even by renouncing the declaration of an end to the war,” he said.
To think that sanctions can bring us to our knees is like chasing utopian dreams for people who don’t care.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions are exacerbating our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which was highlighted by the US leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, he highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months: “If another country on the issue of nuclear disarmament were South Korea rather than the United States, the issue of nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula would not have come to such a dead end.”
But Ri’s tone changed dramatically compared to last year when he told the UN General Assembly that when “Mr. President Evil” Trump called Kim a “rocket gentleman” on a suicide mission, it was absolutely inevitable that North Korea’s missiles would be directed at the United States.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, boasted of Kim’s courage to take steps toward disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea meets the demands for nuclear disarmament.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timeline for doing so, saying that “if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia have said the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
But US Secretary of State Mike Pomeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that “Security Council sanctions must be resolutely continued without concessions until complete and conclusive evidence-based nuclear disarmament has taken place.”
The Security Council unanimously approved sanctions against North Korea since 2006 aimed at preventing funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to loosen the ground for another meeting.
