Harvard Students Learn to Rest Enough
A new course at Harvard University this year encouraged all of its students to sleep more in order to combat the growing culture of macho in studies, caffeine consumption, and staying awake at night
One academic found that in the best university in the world, students often do not even have a basic knowledge of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and Brigham City, a specialist in women’s hospitals, has prepared a course that he says is the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration to prepare this course visited him after talking about the effects of lack of sleep on learning.
“At the end of the talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told about this now, in the final year of my studies?’
She said no one had told her the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course is offered for the first time this year. It explains to students how the most important habits of quality sleep help to achieve academic and sports results, improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services department, said the university decided to offer the course after it found that students were severely short of sleep during the week.
The hour-long course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section is a photo of the dorm room, where students can click on a cup of coffee, curtains, exercise equipment and books to learn about the effects of caffeine, light, how lack of sleep affects sports performance, and how important going to bed routines are.
In the next section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons that encourage participants to reflect on their daily routines.
“We understand that this will not immediately change the behavior of the students.
But we think they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health consequences when you choose to smoke,” explained Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride not to sleep through the night, according to him, still exists. Modern technology and increasing pressure on students led to the growing problem of lack of sleep.
“Ensuring students get enough and get a good night’s sleep should be their secret weapon in the fight against stress, exhaustion and anxiety,” he said, “even to avoid gaining weight because lack of sleep switches the brain to starvation mode, so students are constantly hungry.”
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler take the course when he attended one of his courses last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to ask for an affordable course for the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to invite all postgraduate students to take this course before they start attending this competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set an alarm clock for when it’s time to go to sleep, just as it’s time to go to bed, and to beware of the harmful effects of blue light emitted by electronic devices and LED lights, as they can knock your circadian rhythm out of balance, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
