The National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Bats
A new study, conducted at a Scottish Highlands estate, aims to reveal how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
The findings are expected to provide new insights into the behaviour of unique flying mammals and provide some guidance for future conservation activities.
Researchers from the National Trust for Scotland will be tracking dwarf bats, soprano bats, brown-eared mice and waterfowl in the Wester Ross Inverevo Gardens.
In certain areas of the territory, special recorders will be placed to track the activity of bats throughout the season.
The National Health Service staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile tests with hand-held detectors.
An expert analysis of all sound recordings will determine the frequency of signals emitted by bats and one or another type of activity.
A map of habitable areas and a report will then be created to help shape a detailed picture of behaviour across the landscape.
Rob Dewar, conservation adviser at the National Trust for Scotland (NTS), hopes the results will reveal which residential areas are the most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat maintenance, such as grassland creation, as well as how to best care for wooded areas so that they are suitable for bats and other related species.
Over the past century, bat populations in Scotland and the UK have declined.
They are threatened by construction and real estate development works affecting the hatcheries and destroying residential areas.
There are also threats from wind turbines and lightning, as do flycatchers, some chemicals used to process building materials, and domestic cats hunting.
The bats are not really blind.
However, catching prey during night hunting helps ears more than eyes.
Bats accurately determine the location of insects or obstacles in the flight path by sophisticated echolocation.
The NTS, responsible for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
There are ten trained experts who regularly carry out investigations, hatchery inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organization has even created Scotland’s first and only bat-specific sanctuary at Dumfries and Galloway’s Threeve Manor, home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
The landlord, David Thompson, says that the territory of the manor is ideal for them.
“We have a great place for bats at Threeve Manor,” he said.
– We have old buildings, lots of mature trees and great areas to live in.
But we don’t know much about bats yet, so working here and elsewhere will help you better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stressed that it was crucial to check for the presence of bats before starting maintenance work on the site, as accidental destruction of one hatchery could kill up to 400 females and juveniles, which could lead to the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats shall be protected and it shall be prohibited to kill, tease or disturb them, as well as it shall be prohibited to destroy their hatcheries.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an official at the Scottish Bat Foundation, urged the public to help rescue the bats.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we don't even know how many native populations are doing."
